<br>
Range slots, missed out Othmir Prexus Totem and Talisman of benevolence, as 2 high end items... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utauronoftunare.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tauron of Tunare</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(9/5/01 1:06:20 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The value of wisdom at high-end game</span><hr size=1> The Breil's druid equipment compilation is useful indeed, but only to 1st approximation. The role of a druid changes and so should the equipment. Being lvl 60 for quite some time now I see myself mostly in 3 situations (in order of importance):<br>
<br>
1) large-scale raids: RESISTS, MANA, HP, AC<br>
2) one group dungeon crawls: AC, MANA, HP, RESISTS<br>
3) soloing: AC, MANA, HP, RESISTS<br>
<br>
So MANA and HP are of similar usefulness in any situation (but bear in mind that at lvl 55+ the heal rate is 2.44 HP per MANA); while AC and RESISTS have differing usefulness depending on the situation. This is why I always carry with me at least 2 ten-slot bags full of resist and AC gear to swap according to need (plus some other items so I can dress elegantly for special occasions =)<br>
<br>
My point is that having a list like Briel's compilation is nice and fine but use your head and shoot for flexibility as well, since druids are one of the most flexible classes in EQ. Also bear in mind that high-end game after you reach lvl 60 or close to it is fairly different.<br>
<br>
Tau <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utauronoftunare.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tauron of Tunare</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(9/5/01 1:18:07 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Question about wisdom</span><hr size=1> After you are past the 200 wisdom cap, how much mana, if at all, does extra wisdom add?<br>
<br>
I usually find 3 answers to this:<br>
<br>
1) It doesn't add anything.<br>
2) It adds 1 mana for every 2 wisdom past 200<br>
3) It adds 1 mana for every 1 wisdom past 200<br>
<br>
Does anyone know what it really does and have some evidence to back it up?<br>
<br>
Thanks,<br>
